2500|$|The FQPA {{established}} a new safety standard (reasonable certainty of no harm) {{that must be}} applied to all food commodities. In addition to the new standard the EPA now has to consider the specific risks pesticides might have for infants and children. The FQPA required the re-testing of all existing pesticide tolerance levels within 10 years. [...] When assessing this risk <b>the</b> <b>EPA</b> <b>is</b> required {{to take into account}} the “aggregate risk” (the exposure to a pesticide from multiple sources) and the “cumulative exposure” to pesticides with similar mechanisms of toxicity. To do this <b>the</b> <b>EPA</b> <b>is</b> required to establish new science polices to assess the risks. [...] The FQPA requires the EPA to set tolerances for pesticide uses that fall under section 18 of the Federal Insecticide, Fungicide and Rodenticide Act (emergency exemptions).|$|E
2500|$|The FQPA {{requires}} the EPA {{to establish a}} list of pests that are considered significant to public health and to give special consideration to pesticides with public health uses. [...] <b>The</b> <b>EPA</b> <b>is</b> also required to provide maintenance fee waivers to and encourage the safe and necessary use of methods/pesticides that either combat or control pests that have been deemed of public health importance. The EPA also provides waiver fees for the pesticides used on pests that are deemed of public health importance.|$|E
