5000|$|The Environmental Protection Agency started {{investigating}} {{environmental issues}} at the Eagle Harbor site in 1971. Studies showed {{a high concentration of}} PAH pollution in the harbor and related it to liver lesions in fish. The Eagle Harbor site (called the [...] "Wyckoff" [...] site by <b>the</b> <b>EPA)</b> <b>was</b> put on <b>the</b> Superfund list in 1987 for PAH, heavy metals and PCB pollution. [...] The West Seattle site (called the [...] "Pacific Sound Resources" [...] site by <b>the</b> <b>EPA)</b> <b>was</b> put on <b>the</b> Superfund list in 1994. The company renamed itself as Pacific Sound Resources and, due to expenses associated with clean-up, the company went bankrupt in 1993.|$|R
